Can someone please explain why we treat the recursions as O(1) when getting the time for each subproblem in the formula of the dynamic programming time complexity ?
Can someone please explain why we treat the recursions as O(1) when getting the time for each subproblem in the formula of the dynamic programming time complexity ?

because 1. we cannot be counting the cost of recursion again in time/subproblem since that would be double-counting (the #subproblems value already accounts for all distinct recursive subproblems), 2. so the only remaining cost is the cost of non-recursive work which is theta(1).

if T(n) = 2T(n-2), you see that every time you recurse, the problem size gets twice as big right? Expand out the right side by the definition of T(n), you get: T(n)=2T(n-2) = 2(2T(n-4)) = 2(2(2T(n-6))) = 2(2(2(2T(n-8))))... How many recursive calls do you need to make until you hit one of the base cases (base cases are T(1) = 1, T(2)=1)? This is roughly equivalent to asking 'How many times can we subtract 2 from n?' The answer is that we must recurse n/2 times. Because we make n/2 recursive calls, and each recursive call doubles our (constant time) work, the overall time is 2^(n/2). Make sense?

I'm an old-time programmer who learned his trade in the trenches, not at school, and all this seems unnecessarily complicated to me. Recursion is conceptually elegant, but inefficient if for no other reason that it requires the overhead of a function call to do what could be done in a simple loop using local variables. The "memoization" idea seems to involve creating a global variable as a way of sneaking local variables past the thought police. 

When it comes down to it, everything boils down to machine code, and the most efficient algorithm is the one that requires the fewest instruction cycles. We weren't necessarily worse programmers than the computer scientists, but we had to contend with real-world limitations. Primitive equipment required primitive methods. 

The first computer I worked with had 4000 6-bit characters of core storage (aka RAM), instruction timings in milliseconds, and no OS. A good programmer was one who could squeeze every ounce of performance out of that beast, and since the biggest program you could write wasn't much more than 1000 lines, if that, you didn't have to worry about spaghettification, memory management and all the rest of it. We evolved as the equipment evolved, and we came up with methods that the computer scientists might have learned from. Now you have code that struggles to get by with a mere 8Gb of RAM and runs slowly on a 3GHz CPU.

Why is it called dynamic programming when it is basically divide and conquer, and in the case of using recursion, it is basically cached recursion?  The term dynamic is generally used more for something that is not fixed such as dynamic routing when you drive to work.  You do not insist on driving the same exact route, you instead decide which route to take based on traffic patterns, construction... as you are driving.  In  contrast, a static algorithm would be something "hardwired" that is not flexible such as a fixed sorting algorithm that doesn't "care" what the input is, it just sorts it using the same method each time.  Computer Science (in my opinion) uses some "whacked out" (inaccurate) terms.

I understand that the time per subproblem is indegree(v), or the number of incoming edges to V. But why does he then change that to indegree(v) + 1? What is the "+ 1" for?

If you take the code then you have two loops: The outer loop over all vertices (no. subproblems) and the inner loop over all adjacent vertices (here in-degree). Because of the Handshaking Lemma, the inner loop runs in time |E|*O(1) in total. However, one outer loop (i.e., per vertex) has a time complexity of O(1) plus the inner loop and thus, the time per subproblem you spend is O(1) + deg(v)*O(1), in total  |V|*O(1) + |E|*O(1), i.e., O(|V|+|E|).

Some Micro-Improvements for Bottom Up that just popped into mind: 
* If we'd pass the fib[k-1] (as f_in_previous_iteration), 
* * then we wouldnt need to go and find it from far-away memory. Anyway memory access is more expensive than most think.
* * * includes removing the need to calc address &fibKm1 = &fib + k - 1;
* the check: if k <= 2: f=1;     can be moved out from the for-loop. IF statement is generally bad practice anyway (stops all blocks of CPU that depend on it)
* * have 2 functions, 1st does k==1 or ==2 and the rest and the rcursive part never checks it, just starts from 3
* range(1; n+1).   N+1 is constant and should be calculated once per fib() call
* * do you mean while k < n + 1? Or actually the last iteration would calc N+1 and give wrong answer?
* variable f is irrelevant - could just use f[k] everywhere
* For  f[k] actually &f + k    is done on CPU
* * pointer arithmetics would be faster as this instruction is not needed.

C++ proto-code for those 1st thoughts:

int  f[N] = {1, 1};    // fill first with 1st 2 numbers = 1
int* const fEnd = f+N;
int* f_m2 = f++;    // pointer to fib[k-2]
int* f_m1 = f++;   // pointer to fib[k-1]
while (++f < fEnd) {
     *f = *f_m1 + *f_m2; // use pointers to get & set
       f_m2++; f_m1++; // inc all 3 pointers
}
return *f;

There are some incoming edges to vertex v. The shortest path to v comes through one of those edges. We don't know which one. So before solving the problem of finding shortest path to v we have solve smaller problems of finding shortest path to the parent vertices. If we have 2 incoming edges u1 -> v and u2 -> v, then we have to first find the shortest paths to vertices u1 and u2. Once we know them we can choose one edge between u1 -> v and u2 -> v which will result in the shortest path to v.

In fact, if you go into a typical company and code some wizbang 'elegant' algorithm, you'll be asked to redo it so that it can be supported by normal people.

Development is about getting results and accomplishing it in a way that is supportable and extensible by others.

It really does depend on the company culture, and considerations like how often others will have to revise it, and by how much, and the relative resource constraints like runtime. For larger companies and projects with longterm or possibly indefinite development lifetimes (such as developing commercial software), I could definitely see this being the case, but in my experience as a programmer for smaller game companies, this hasn't really been the case. But that's involved small teams and a massive focus on any performance optimizations possible (a runtime reduction of only a few percent can mean the difference between playable frame rates and a juddery mess).

I wish I could ask a question from the audience. Like this one: can't we just memoize cyclic recurrences as they happen to avoid infinite loops, instead of doing the multiple graph version solution (49:17) ?

You would have to have two lookups minimum and then a bit more guessing.

1. One for function results
2. One for unfinished functions.

Then your logic would have to see that you are asking for the result of something not yet finished, and then track the number of times you've hit it because at some point you either will indefinitely hit it OR you will be close to finishing OR you will have an unsolvable problem OR you went down the wrong tree branch...the problem there is then you have to have intuition, which without AI, your code cannot do even decently...you leave the realm of Dynamic Programming and enter into Artificial-Intelligence/Machine-Learning or requiring manual inputs.

The graph versions allows one to both visually (when creating the algorithm) and logically (when applying it) determine which cyclic recurrences are indefinite-recursions/infinite-loops and which ones are part of the shortest path. *Sometimes* a short or *THE SHORTEST* path might include a repetition such as:

1. A* pathing that updates as the target moves
2. Paths that involve moving-obstacles/state-changing-paths
3. and flow of particulates/liquids/lighting

I don't think you understand how DP works. If you do it correctly, the lookup process is guaranteed to be O(1).
....but if the dictionary lookup process takes longer than all the requisite recursion needed to yield an answer, DP is pointless.

you could also be dealing with an issue of heap vs stack allocation, though, too, given he just used a simple example, Fibonacci, which given a really large number might not cause issues for you in most programming languages and environments even, but escalate it from Fibonacci to something like a math parsing engine or something with more variants, then it's not so simple.

So, given a more detailed/complex problem space, having too many recursions can actually kill your program's speed (assuming unlimited or near unlimited stack space pre-allocated for method params/data) OR even worse, it could cause an issue known as *stack-overflow* by going over the number of items that can rest on the stack before you must begin emptying it or resolving recursions. Infinite method chaining/recursions can quickly overflow the stack, but so, too can a complex recursion tree that never resolves or fails to resolve in a reasonable number of recursions.

It all just depends on what you are doing and how deep you can go vs how you can mitigate known issues beforehand. But, he did cover this briefly towards the beginning where he added in the caveat that assumes your hashing algorithm is good enough to be represented by a near constant lookup time. As long as your hashing algorithm used (if using dictionary or hash) is better than 3 levels of recursion, then you are already optimized i that sense.

But, if you don't learn the mechanics behind the technique, then it won't matter whether full-blown brute-force recursion or memoization supported recursion/looping is better because you'll only have 1 of the two tools necessary...and you know what they say about only having a hammer? (if you only have a hammer, then every problem will be a nail).
